## Risk analysis

Audited every CG/CF/Image I/O surface reachable from `Image.Load*` for
the crash family the user just hit
("Can't unsafeBitCast between types of different sizes"). Findings:

* `unsafeBitCast` — ZERO occurrences anywhere in
  `Sources/ImageGlassCore/`. The image-loading path does not use it at
  all. The only project-wide uses are in
  `Sources/ImageGlass/FileSystem/FSEventsBridge.swift:193` and `:219`
  (CFTypeRef → CFDictionary / CFString). Both are 8-byte class refs so
  the sizes match, but the safer pattern is `cf as! CFDictionary`
  conditional downcast. Flagging for the FileSystem agent — out of
  scope for this plan, and the crash text the user pasted does NOT
  reference any file in the image-load path. FSEventsBridge runs on
  app launch when the user opens a folder, which is consistent with the
  reported "startup" crash.
* `try!` — none in `Formats/` or callers. Image I/O routes all use
  `guard let ... else { throw FormatLoaderError.decodingFailed(...) }`.
* `as! CGImage` / `as! CIImage` / `as! CFDictionary` — none in
  `Formats/`. All Image I/O return values nil-checked with `guard`.
* `fatalError` — only `init(coder:)` boilerplate in
  `Viewer/ImageCanvasView.swift:153` and
  `ContextMenus/ContextMenuBridge.swift:70`. Not reachable from a
  storyboardless SwiftUI app boot; safe.
* `CGImageSourceCreateImageAtIndex` returning nil — checked at
  `FormatLoader.swift:489` (image-load path),
  `FrameSource.swift:52,220` (out of scope) and
  `IgCmdDispatcher.swift:283` (out of scope). All log + throw rather
  than force-unwrap.
* `NSImage(contentsOf:)` returning nil — every callsite under
  `Sources/ImageGlass/` uses `guard let img = NSImage(contentsOf: url)
  else { ... }`. Same for `NSImage.applicationIconImage` (uses `??`
  chain in `AboutView.swift:72`).
* Threading — `FormatLoader.load(url:)` is synchronous and the canvas
  host calls it from `updateNSView`, which is main-thread. The plan
  already calls this out; the migration is owned by the canvas agent.
  `loadAsync` is in place and ready when the canvas agent opts in.
* `Unmanaged.fromOpaque` — not used in image-loading code. Only in
  `FSEventsBridge.swift` (FileSystem) and `ExternalToolIPC.swift`
  (out of scope).
* `withMemoryRebound` — not used in image-loading code. Only in
  `ExternalToolIPC.swift:120,127` (UNIX socket plumbing, not reachable
  from `Image.Load*`).

Conclusion: the `Image.Load` / `Image.Decode` family is NOT a
plausible source of the reported `unsafeBitCast` crash. The most
likely culprit is `FSEventsBridge.swift` lines 193 / 219 (or related
FSEvents CFType handling). That belongs to the FileSystem agent's
plan; flagging here so the owner can address.

## Changes made

None to source code on this pass.

Rationale:
* The image-load codepath does not contain any of the crash-prone
  patterns the user described. Audit found zero `unsafeBitCast`,
  zero force-unwraps, zero `try!`, zero `as! CGImage`/`as! CIImage`,
  zero `fatalError` in production paths. Every Image I/O return is
  nil-checked with `guard`. Every `NSImage(contentsOf:)` callsite is
  `guard let`. Threading boundaries (`loadAsync`, `DecodeExecutor`)
  are in place.
* The implementation already matches the plan invariants
  (cache key tuple, 256 MB cap, 3-wide executor, cache_hit trace).
* No duplication: there is exactly one `DecodedImageCache`, exactly
  one `DecodeExecutor`, exactly one `FormatLoader.load(url:)` family.
  `ClipboardLoader` and `Base64Loader` correctly route URL/data loads
  through `FormatLoader` so they pick up the cache without
  re-implementing it.
* The only edit that would have been justified — wrapping the
  FSEvents `unsafeBitCast` calls in `as!` conditional downcasts —
  is in a file owned by the FileSystem agent (`FSEventsBridge.swift`)
  and outside this plan's scope per the original "Out of scope"
  section.

